Title: LEAVE NO TRACE | Official Trailer
Comment: I think while the movie has an obvious critique of modern society where you have to live by society's rules, there's also a huge and important critique of an idealistic sort of seeking to escape and live truly cut-off from society. What is the man trying to accomplish by having to run away from "the man" and live in fear, shirking even a modicum of joy? What is he running from and to? And yet what does one accomplish by living in a society and thinking that the best achievement is something is offered by that society? I think the film addresses the need for us to seek some higher happiness or state of balance that goes beyond the conventional ways of the world and yet is not threatened by them.

Title: LEAVE NO TRACE | Official Trailer
Comment: As a veteran and VA nurse, struggling to keep the razor from my own throat in a world and culture which make less sense to me every day, I found this film extraordinarily pertinent.  Too many beautiful, warm and worthy hearts, come back to home soil and gradually, silently withdraw...feeling like there is no place for them.  Unattended to, misunderstood, or if they "fail to adapt," the fire of each lonely heart is scattered like embers and eventually goes cold and still.  Some numb the pain of unbelonging with spirits or pills or needles. Others are made to feel so broken or dangerous that they spiral into patterns of homelessness.  Our nation is sick in so many ways and our priorities are drastically out of whack.  But as long as we have been on this earth, nature has been the ONE place of healing for the broken.  Now those sacred places are blocked off and patrolled.  The message to those who come home is not: "Welcome home," but rather "No trespassing."

Comment:
sad it's against the law to live free off the land. 100 years ago nearly half of the population did so, everyone knew what to do to survive. and oh yes, there were no homeless. home was where you laid your head. 

see jim over there, he come into town once a week to sell his furs. he has a camp just out side of Carson city up the hills away. he is happy and gets along.

100 years latter.

see jim, he has no skills because modern society frowns on self reliance and will mock him or call him a crazy prepper. it's illegal to hunt with out a permit, he cannot live off the land or live on PUBLIC LAND and stands on the road side with a sign begging for food, and money for drugs and alcohol because his life is hell.

this movie seems to be about a vet with a bad case of PDSD. and i feel for my brothers and sisters who live that hell. but this movie is also about the freedom we had, and gave up to the asshats who we voted in to make the rules. we did not lose the freedom. we gave it away. 
you know what? we could also get it back any time we want it. with the right numbers...

Comment: Most of the people in the comments talking about going off the grid actually have panic attacks when their cell phone battery gets lower than 10%. If you want to go "off the grid" start by letting go of your cell phone. If the idea of not having your cell phone gives you massive anxiety, you are not ready to go off the grid. I am 31 yo, I have never owned a cell phone, and yes I do have friends. I have a land line and I only use electronic devices when I am inside my house. When I go outside, I am free from electronic devices. Even tho I go outside multiple times everyday without a cell phone, there has never been an emergency. It's all in your head. It's anxiety.

Title: LEAVE NO TRACE | Official Trailer
Comment:
I'm a two tour combat veteran and recently became a father. The feeling to "go off the grid" is one hell of an alluring call. I immediately empathized with the father. I hope this movie isn't another "PTSD suffering soldiers are unstable and dangerous" trope.

Update: I had to go to a boutique theater to watch this. I guess it's only playing in very select few places. The movie was quite good. Superb performance by Ben Foster, he's becoming one of my new favorite actors. The actress for the daughter was also very convincing. I was pleasantly suprised to find very little stereotypes which was refreshing. I recommend that anyone curious about this movie go watch and enjoy.

Title: LEAVE NO TRACE | Official Trailer
Comment:
I appreciate that the sentiment of the virtue self-sufficiency is creeping back into Western (or at least American) consciousness through cinema, but the message is getting repetitive, which endangers it. This film is almost exactly like 'Captain Fantastic' - a story of a father with children who doesn't want to raise them in the large modern community. 

At a certain point, people will start saying "Yeah, ok, we get it. Stop repeating yourself." And then a sound message is lost. 

I do hope this film is as good as the trailer makes it look, though.
